Edible wild plants recognition¶

Project: Develop a model that would recognize 62 different types of wild edible plants from images¶

This notebook in the implementation of the Capstone Project for the Udacity Machine Learning Engineer Nanodegree. The project aims to identify wild edible plants from images. I have put together a custom dataset for 62 edible wild plants.

The classification problem to be solved is to identify if a given picture is that of one of the 62 edible wild plants included in the dataset. The algorithm should return either one of the 62 plants, with the related additional information, with the highest resemblance to the given picture, or decide if the given picture depicts none of the plants in the dataset.

We start by reading the images dataset.

# define function to load the dataset
def load_dataset(path):
    data = load_files(path,categories=None)
    files = np.array(data['filenames'])
    labels = np.array(data['target'])
    #np.utils.to_categorical is used to convert array of labeled data(from 0 to nb_classes-1) to one-hot vector.
    one_hot_targets = np_utils.to_categorical(labels)
    return files, labels, one_hot_targets

#load the dataset
plant_files, plant_labels, plant_targets = load_dataset('./dataset')

Preprocess the data¶

The images are in .jpg format. The dimensions are not manually standardized, but this will be one step of the data preparation – to bring all the images to 100x100px. So far, I have made sure that no image exceeds 300KB, to keep the database within reasonable size limits.

As the dataset is gathered off the internet, the pictures come in different sizes and quality levels. At first I would need to pre-process the data. I would try the following actions:

  • Obtain an uniform aspect ratio – by cropping to squares (centered)
  • Perform Image scaling – scale to 100x100px
  • Normalize image inputs – this makes convergence faster while training the network. Data normalization is done by subtracting the mean from each pixel, and then dividing the result by the standard deviation
  • Perform Data Augmentation – generate more pictures from the existing ones, by rotation, scaling or flipping - this will be done directly with keras, later, when fitting the model

The function crop centers the image and crops it around the center. The function resize_and_crop does maintain the full image, but at a reduced scale. The function pathlist2imagelist returns a list of images, from a list of file paths, while also resizing and cropping them and normalizing the image input.

In [22]:
import cv2
from matplotlib import pyplot as plt
import imgaug
from keras.preprocessing.image import img_to_array
from keras.applications.vgg16 import preprocess_input
import sys

#make sure there are no special characters in the path (eg. "'") - or the cv2.imread will return None
def crop(path):
    #open image
    img = cv2.imread(path)
    #get center of image
    x = int(img.shape[0]/2)
    y = int(img.shape[1]/2)
    #crop 50px to the left/right and top/down
    img = img[x-50:x+50,y-50:y+50,:]
    height, width, channels = img.shape
    if height <100 or width <100 or channels < 3:
        print("-----------------------------")
        print("------ Image too small ------", path, "shape: ", height, width, channels)
        sys.exit()
    return img

def resize_and_crop(path):
    desired_size = 100
    im = cv2.imread(path)
    old_size = im.shape[:2] # old_size is in (height, width) format
    ratio = float(desired_size)/max(old_size)
    new_size = tuple([int(x*ratio) for x in old_size])

    # new_size should be in (width, height) format
    im = cv2.resize(im, (new_size[1], new_size[0]))
    delta_w = desired_size - new_size[1]
    delta_h = desired_size - new_size[0]
    top, bottom = delta_h//2, delta_h-(delta_h//2)
    left, right = delta_w//2, delta_w-(delta_w//2)
    #padding
    color = [0, 0, 0]
    new_im = cv2.copyMakeBorder(im, top, bottom, left, right, cv2.BORDER_CONSTANT, value=color)
    return new_im

def normalize_image_inputs(image):
    norm_image = cv2.normalize(image, None, alpha=0, beta=1, norm_type=cv2.NORM_MINMAX, dtype=cv2.CV_32F)
    return norm_image

# get a list of images from a list of paths
def pathlist2imagelist(pathlist):
    imagelist = []
    for path in pathlist:
        #print("path =", path)
        #img = crop(path)
        img = resize_and_crop(path)
        img_norm = normalize_image_inputs(img)
        
        #preprocess image list to fit keras expected input format -  4D array (4D tensor) [nb_samples,rows,columns,channels]
        # convert the image pixels to a numpy array
        img_norm = img_to_array(img_norm)
        # prepare the image for the VGG model
        img_exp = np.expand_dims(img_norm, axis=0)
        
        imagelist.append(img_exp)
        #if img_norm[0].shape is not 100 or img_norm[1].shape is not 100 or img_norm[2].shape is not 3:
            #print("image shape: ",img_norm.shape, path)
    #print("IMagelist shape", imagelist[0].shape, imagelist[1].shape,imagelist[2].shape)
    imglist = np.vstack(imagelist)
    return imglist

Build the transfer learning model¶

I will build my model using transfer learning. I have chosen the VGG16 model, and I first have to import the weights of the VGG-16 model, trained on ImageNet. ImageNet is a project which aims to provide a large image database for research purposes. It contains more than 14 million images which belong to more than 20,000 classes ( or synsets ) I am removing the output layer, and will replace it with a series of custom layers: two Dense layers, with dropout, and a softmax layer at the end, with the 62 classes. I am adding the two Dense layers with Dropout because I have noticed that the model tends to overfit quite a lot. I am also freezing the first 10 layers of the VGG16 model, in order to save computing power.Freezing all of them resulted in very low accuracy, and freezing only 6 layers resulted also in a slightly lower accuracy.

In [24]:
from keras.applications.vgg16 import VGG16
from keras.preprocessing import image
from keras.layers import Dropout, Flatten, Dense, GlobalAveragePooling2D, Conv2D, MaxPooling2D
from keras.models import Sequential, Model 
from keras import optimizers
from keras.callbacks import ModelCheckpoint

VGG16_model = VGG16(weights='imagenet', include_top=False, input_tensor=None, input_shape=(100,100,3), pooling=None, classes=62)

# Freeze all the 19 layers, which I don't want to retrain
#for layer in VGG16_model.layers[:18]:
#for layer in VGG16_model.layers[:14]:
for layer in VGG16_model.layers[:10]:
#for layer in VGG16_model.layers[:6]:
    layer.trainable = False

#Adding custom Layers 
x = VGG16_model.output
x = Flatten()(x)
x = Dense(1024, activation="relu")(x)
x = Dropout(0.8)(x)
x = Dense(1024, activation="relu")(x)
x = Dropout(0.8)(x)
#output layer with 62 classes as possible predictions
predictions = Dense(62, activation="softmax")(x)

Split the training, dev and test datasets, and fit the model¶

To preserve the class balances across the train/test datasets, I am using the Stratified K-Folds cross-validator. This cross-validation object is a variation of KFold that returns stratified folds. The folds are made by preserving the percentage of samples for each class.

Because I am training the model on my laptop's GPU, I have to be extra sensible to performance and training time. For this, I did have to apply some restrictions that are potentially limiting the final model accuracy:

  • reduce images to 100x100px, as opposed to the 224x224px standard input size of the VGG16 model
  • choose only 5 splits for the StratifiedKFold, instead of the unually used 10 splits
  • train on a very limited number of epochs (I have experimented with 1-10 epochs)

Also, because of the long training time, I am saving the weights after each epoch, if they improve.

I do the fitting using Keras's ImageDataGenerator, applying some data augmentation. I chose to do this, and it has improved my model's accuracy, as the dataset size is still quite limited.

In [26]:
from sklearn.model_selection import StratifiedKFold
from keras.preprocessing.image import ImageDataGenerator
from keras.applications.vgg16 import decode_predictions

skf = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=10, random_state=12)
avg_loss = []
avg_acc = []
# Loop through the indices the split() method returns
for index, (train_index, test_index) in enumerate(skf.split(plant_files, plant_labels)):
    print("Training on fold " + str(index+1) + "/10.............................................")
    # Generate batches from indices
    xtrain, xtest = plant_files[train_index], plant_files[test_index]
    # use one-hot vectors as labels
    ytrain, ytest = plant_targets[train_index], plant_targets[test_index]
    
    # Clear the model, and create it
    model = None
    model = Model(input = VGG16_model.input, output = predictions)
    
    # load best weights so far
    model.load_weights("final_model_weights.hdf5")
    
    # if your targets are one-hot encoded, use categorical_crossentropy, but if your targets are integers, use sparse_categorical_crossentropy
    model.compile(loss = "categorical_crossentropy", optimizer = optimizers.SGD(lr=0.0001, momentum=0.7), metrics=['accuracy'])
    #model.compile(loss = "categorical_crossentropy", optimizer = optimizers.SGD(lr=0.0001, momentum=0.9), metrics={'output_a': 'accuracy', 'output_b': 'precision'})
    #model.compile(loss = "sparse_categorical_crossentropy", optimizer = optimizers.SGD(lr=0.0001, momentum=0.9), metrics=["accuracy"])

    # create checkpoint after each epoch in the fitting process
    filepath="final_model_weights.hdf5"
    checkpoint = ModelCheckpoint(filepath, monitor='val_acc', verbose=1, save_best_only=True, save_weights_only=False, mode='max', period=1)
    callbacks_list = [checkpoint] 
    
    # open all the images from the xtrain and ytrain paths, crop and normalize them
    xtrain_imagelist = pathlist2imagelist(xtrain)
    xtest_imagelist = pathlist2imagelist(xtest)
    
    # fit the model - only a few epochs, to save time
    #model.fit(xtrain_imagelist, ytrain, validation_data=(xtest_imagelist, ytest), epochs=1, callbacks=callbacks_list, verbose=1)
    
    #fit the model with image augmentation
    datagen = ImageDataGenerator(rotation_range=20, width_shift_range=0.2, height_shift_range=0.2, horizontal_flip=True)
    #fit it on the data - this will calculate any statistics required to actually perform the transforms on the image data.
    datagen.fit(xtrain_imagelist)
    # steps_per_epoch * batch_size images will be loaded per each epoch
    model.fit_generator(datagen.flow(xtrain_imagelist, ytrain, batch_size=32), steps_per_epoch=1200, validation_data=(xtest_imagelist, ytest), epochs=1, callbacks=callbacks_list, verbose=1)
    
    #evaluate and store the accuracy
    loss, accuracy = model.evaluate(xtest_imagelist, ytest, verbose=1)
    avg_loss.append(loss)
    avg_acc.append(accuracy)

Creating the Benchmark model¶

For the benchmark model I have chosen a simple vanilla CNN.

The model contains 2 Conv layers, separated by a Pooling layer each, to reduce the number of parameters, and to make the feature detection invariant to scale and orientation changes. To connect the output of the pooling layer to the last 2 fully connected layers, we need to flatten this output into a single tensor. The last fully connected layer contains the softmax to the 62 classes.

In [28]:
vanilla_model = Sequential()
vanilla_model.add(Conv2D(32, kernel_size=(5, 5), strides=(1, 1),
                 activation='relu',
                 input_shape=(100,100,3)))
vanilla_model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2), strides=(2, 2)))
vanilla_model.add(Conv2D(64, (5, 5), activation='relu'))
vanilla_model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
vanilla_model.add(Flatten())
vanilla_model.add(Dense(1000, activation='relu'))
vanilla_model.add(Dense(62, activation='softmax'))

print(vanilla_model.summary())

Test the models on new data¶

After having tested the models in the dev set, it is time to test the model on new data - that the model has never seen. I have built a separate folder for the test data, with 5 images per class - so 310 test images in total.

In [30]:
#load the test dataset
plant_files_test, plant_labels_test, plant_targets_test = load_dataset('./dataset-test')
#convert list of paths to list of images
plant_files_test_imagelist = pathlist2imagelist(plant_files_test)
#evaluate the accuracy on the test set
print("Testing the VGG16 model ...")
model.load_weights("final_model_weights.hdf5")
pred_test_labels = model.predict(plant_files_test_imagelist)
loss, accuracy = model.evaluate(plant_files_test_imagelist, plant_targets_test, verbose=1)
print("Test dataset loss = ", loss,"; accuracy = ", accuracy)

print("Testing the vanilla model ...")
vanilla_model.load_weights("vanilla_model_weights.hdf5")
vanilla_loss, vanilla_accuracy = vanilla_model.evaluate(plant_files_test_imagelist, plant_targets_test, verbose=1)
print("Test dataset loss = ", vanilla_loss,"; accuracy = ", vanilla_accuracy)

Understanding and exploring the results¶

TO be able to understand where the model is doign well,and where it needs improvement, I am showing a confusion matrix.

As due to the large number of classes it is not very readable, I am also showing the number of correct predictions, per class, out of the 5 maximmum correct predictions. I am using these to target the classes where the algorithm performs the worst, and invest time to find and provide more training images.

In [31]:
#confusion matrix for text data
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import itertools
#Your input to confusion_matrix must be an array of int not one hot encodings

Provide an interface for user images¶

Because a potential usage of this model would be usage on a mobile app, it is important to be able to test with user images. These should be added to the folder "dataset-user_images",and the model will predict their classes.

In [32]:
#predict the class for an user image
from keras.applications.vgg16 import decode_predictions

path = './dataset-user_images'
imgs = glob(path + "/*.jpg")

for i in imgs:
    print("Predicting image ", i)
    img = resize_and_crop(i)
    plt.imshow(img, cmap = 'gray', interpolation = 'bicubic')
    plt.xticks([]), plt.yticks([])  # to hide tick values on X and Y axis
    plt.show()
    img = img_to_array(img)
    img = np.expand_dims(img, axis=0)
    img = preprocess_input(img)
    predicted_classes = model.predict(img)    
    predicted_class = predicted_classes.argmax(axis=-1)
    confidence = predicted_classes.max()
    if confidence >= 0.8 :
        print("Predicted class for above image: ", plant_names[int(predicted_class)], predicted_class, ", with confidence level ", confidence)
        print("Details on this plant: ")
        print(plant_details[plant_names[int(predicted_class)]])
    else:
        print("This image does not represent a plant from the 62 wild edible plants dataset.")
    print("---------------------------------------------------")
